GOEntry.name: molecular_function
GOEntry.definition: Elemental activities, such as catalysis or binding, describing the actions of a gene product at the molecular level. A given gene product may exhibit one or more molecular functions.

GOEntry.name: motor activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of movement along a polymeric molecule such as a microfilament or microtubule, coupled to the hydrolysis of a nucleoside triphosphate.

GOEntry.name: microfilament motor activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of movement along a microfilament, coupled to the hydrolysis of a nucleoside triphosphate (usually ATP).

GOEntry.name: microtubule motor activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of movement along a microtubule, coupled to the hydrolysis of a nucleoside triphosphate (usually ATP).

GOEntry.name: minus-end-directed microtubule motor activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of movement along a microtubule toward the minus end, coupled to the hydrolysis of ATP (or GTP).

GOEntry.name: plus-end-directed microtubule motor activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of movement along a microtubule toward the plus end, coupled to the hydrolysis of ATP (or GTP).

GOEntry.name: catalytic activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of a biochemical reaction at physiological temperatures. In biologically catalyzed reactions, the reactants are known as substrates, and the catalysts are naturally occurring macromolecular substances known as enzymes. Enzymes possess specific binding sites for substrates, and are usually composed wholly or largely of protein, but RNA that has catalytic activity (ribozyme) is often also regarded as enzymatic.

GOEntry.name: recombinase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the identification and base-pairing of homologous sequences between single-stranded DNA and double-stranded DNA.

GOEntry.name: C-22 sterol desaturase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the formation of the C-22(23) double bond in the sterol side chain.

GOEntry.name: spliceosomal catalysis
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of a transesterification reaction that is part of spliceosomal mRNA splicing.

GOEntry.name: first spliceosomal transesterification activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the first transesterification reaction of spliceosomal mRNA splicing. The intron branch site adenosine is the nucleophile attacking the 5' splice site, resulting in cleavage at this position. In cis splicing, this is the step that forms a lariat structure of the intron RNA, while it is still joined to the 3' exon.

GOEntry.name: second spliceosomal transesterification activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the second transesterification reaction of spliceosomal mRNA splicing. Ligation of the two exons occurs via a transesterification reaction where the free 3'-hydroxyl group of the 5' exon is the nucleophile attacking the 3' splice site. Non-expressed sequences are now detached from the exons. In cis splicing, the intron is in a lariat structure.

GOEntry.name: glycogen debranching enzyme activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the cleavage of branch points in branched glycogen polymers.

GOEntry.name: 4-alpha-glucanotransferase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a segment of a (1,4)-alpha-D-glucan to a new 4-position in an acceptor, which may be glucose or (1,4)-alpha-D-glucan.

GOEntry.name: amylo-alpha-1,6-glucosidase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of (1,6)-alpha-D-glucosidic branch linkages in glycogen phosphorylase limit dextrin. Limit dextrin is the highly branched core that remains after exhaustive treatment of glycogen with glycogen phosphorylase. It is formed because these enzymes cannot hydrolyze the 1,6 glycosidic linkages present.

GOEntry.name: isoamylase activity

GOEntry.name: dimethylnitrosamine demethylase activity

GOEntry.name: helicase activity

GOEntry.name: RNA helicase activity

GOEntry.name: ATP-dependent helicase activity

GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with major histocompatibility complex molecules; a set of molecules displayed on cell surfaces that are responsible for lymphocyte recognition and antigen presentation.

GOEntry.name: T-cell receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a T-cell receptor, the antigen-recognizing receptor on the surface of T-cells.

GOEntry.name: CD4 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a CD4, a receptor found on the surface of T-cells, monocytes and macrophages.

GOEntry.name: CD8 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a CD8, a receptor found on the surface of thymocytes and cytotoxic and suppressor T-lymphocytes.

GOEntry.name: CD70 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a CD70, a receptor found on the surface of most activated B-cells and some activated T-cells.

GOEntry.name: CD154 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with CD154, a receptor found on the surface of some activated lymphocytes.

GOEntry.name: neuromedin U receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with one or more specific sites on a neuromedin U receptor.

GOEntry.name: peroxisome proliferator activated receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with any of the peroxisome proliferator activated receptors, alpha, beta or gamma.

GOEntry.name: natural killer cell lectin-like receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a lectin-like natural killer cell receptor.

GOEntry.name: host cell surface receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a receptor on the host cell surface.

GOEntry.name: ephrin receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with an ephrin receptor.

GOEntry.name: receptor agonist activity
GOEntry.definition: Interacts with receptors such that the proportion of receptors in the active form is increased.

GOEntry.name: receptor antagonist activity
GOEntry.definition: Interacts with receptors to reduce the action of another ligand, the agonist.

GOEntry.name: Roundabout binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the Roundabout (ROBO) receptor, a transmembrane receptor.

GOEntry.name: low-density lipoprotein receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a low density lipoprotein receptor.

GOEntry.name: dopamine receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the dopamine receptor.

GOEntry.name: RAGE receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the RAGE receptor, the receptor for advanced glycation end-products.

GOEntry.name: GABA receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA, 4-aminobutyrate) receptor.

GOEntry.name: toxin receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a toxin receptor, a receptor for substances that cause injury to living organisms.

GOEntry.name: histidine phosphotransfer kinase activity
GOEntry.definition: Serves as a phospho-His intermediate enabling the transfer of phospho group between a hybrid kinase and a response regulator.

GOEntry.name: activin inhibitor activity
GOEntry.definition: Acts to negatively regulate the activity of activin, a nonsteroidal regulator synthesized in the pituitary gland and gonads that stimulates the secretion of follicle-stimulating hormone.

GOEntry.name: structural molecule activity
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a complex or assembly within or outside a cell.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of ribosome
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the ribosome.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of cell wall
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a cell wall.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of cytoskeleton
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a cytoskeletal structure.

GOEntry.name: extracellular matrix structural constituent
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the extracellular matrix.

GOEntry.name: extracellular matrix structural constituent conferring tensile strength
GOEntry.definition: A constituent of the extracellular matrix that enables the matrix to resist longitudinal stress.

GOEntry.name: extracellular matrix structural constituent conferring compression resistance
GOEntry.definition: A constituent of the extracellular matrix that enables the matrix to resist compressive forces; often a proteoglycan.

GOEntry.name: extracellular matrix constituent conferring elasticity
GOEntry.definition: A component of the extracellular matrix that enables the matrix to recoil after transient stretching.

GOEntry.name: extracellular matrix constituent, lubricant activity
GOEntry.definition: Functions as a lubricant for an extracellular matrix, such as a mucous membrane.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of eye lens
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the lens of an eye.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of chorion (sensu Insecta)
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a chorion. As in, but not restricted to, the true insects (Insecta, ncbi_taxonomy_id:50557).

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of bone
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of bone.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of muscle
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a muscle fiber.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of vitelline membrane (sensu Insecta)
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the vitelline membrane of an egg. As in, but not restricted to, the true insects (Insecta, ncbi_taxonomy_id:50557).

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of peritrophic membrane (sensu Insecta)
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the peritrophic membrane, a tubular sheath of cuticle that shields the epithelial cells of the midgut from the gut contents. As in, but not restricted to, the true insects (Insecta, ncbi_taxonomy_id:50557).

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of nuclear pore
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the nuclear pore complex.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of myelin sheath
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the myelin sheath of a nerve.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of epidermis
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of an epidermal cutaneous structure.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of cutaneous appendage
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of cutaneous epidermal structures such as hairs, scales, or feathers.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of tooth enamel
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of tooth enamel.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of chromatin
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of chromatin.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of cuticle
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a cuticle.

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of cuticle (sensu Insecta)
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a cuticle. As in, but not restricted to, the true insects (Insecta, ncbi_taxonomy_id:50557).

GOEntry.name: structural constituent of cuticle (sensu Nematoda)
GOEntry.definition: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a cuticle. As in, but not restricted to, the roundworms (Nematoda, ncbi_taxonomy_id:6231).

GOEntry.name: transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: amine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of amines, including polyamines, into, out of, within or between cells. Amines are organic compounds that are weakly basic in character and contain an amino (-NH2) or substituted amino group.

GOEntry.name: acetylcholine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of acetylcholine into, out of, within or between cells. Acetylcholine is an acetic acid ester of the organic base choline and functions as a neurotransmitter, released at the synapses of parasympathetic nerves and at neuromuscular junctions.

GOEntry.name: dopamine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of dopamine into, out of, within or between cells. Dopamine is a catecholamine neurotransmitter and a metabolic precursor of noradrenaline and adrenaline.

GOEntry.name: norepinephrine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of norepinephrine into, out of, within or between cells. Norepinephrine (3,4-dihydroxyphenyl-2-aminoethanol) is a hormone secreted by the adrenal medulla and a neurotransmitter in the sympathetic peripheral nervous system and in some tracts of the CNS. It is also the biosynthetic precursor of epinephrine.

GOEntry.name: taurine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of taurine into, out of, within or between cells. Taurine (2-aminoethanesulfonic acid) is a sulphur-containing amino acid derivative which is important in the metabolism of fats.

GOEntry.name: synaptic vesicle amine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of amines into, out of or within synaptic vesicles.

GOEntry.name: monoamine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of monoamines, organic compounds containing one amino group, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: amino acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of amino acids, organic acids containing one or more amino substituents, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: betaine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of betaine, the N-trimethyl derivative of an amino acid, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: methylammonium transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of methylammonium, CH3NH2, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: polyamine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of polyamines, organic compounds containing two or more amino groups, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: urea transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of urea into, out of, within or between cells. Urea is the water soluble compound H2N-CO-NH2, produced in the liver via the ornithine-urea cycle. It is the main nitrogen-containing (urinary) excretion product in ureotelic animals.

GOEntry.name: choline transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of choline into, out of, within or between cells. Choline (2-hydroxyethyltrimethylammonium) is an amino alcohol that occurs widely in living organisms as a constituent of certain types of phospholipids and in the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.

GOEntry.name: serotonin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of serotonin into, out of, within or between cells. Serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine) is a monoamine neurotransmitter occurring in the peripheral and central nervous systems.

GOEntry.name: cadaverine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of cadaverine, 1,5-pentanediamine, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: quaternary ammonium group transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of quaternary ammonium groups into, out of, within or between cells. Quaternary ammonium groups are any compound that can be regarded as derived from ammonium hydroxide or an ammonium salt by replacement of all four hydrogen atoms of the NH4+ ion by organic groups.

GOEntry.name: lipid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of lipids into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: phospholipid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of phospholipids into, out of, within or between cells. Phospholipids are a class of lipids containing phosphoric acid as a mono- or diester.

GOEntry.name: fatty acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of fatty acids into, out of, within or between cells. Fatty acids are aliphatic monocarboxylic acids liberated from naturally occurring fats and oils by hydrolysis.

GOEntry.name: fatty acyl transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a fatty acyl group into, out of, within or between cells. A fatty acyl group is any acyl group derived from a fatty acid.

GOEntry.name: sterol transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of sterols into, out of, within or between cells. Sterol are steroids with one or more hydroxyl groups and a hydrocarbon side-chain in the molecule.

GOEntry.name: glycolipid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of glycolipids, compounds containing (usually) 1-4 linked monosaccharide residues joined by a glycosyl linkage to a lipid, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: sphingolipid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of sphingolipids into, out of, within or between cells. Sphingolipids are a class of lipids containing the long-chain amine diol sphingosine or a closely related base (a sphingoid).

GOEntry.name: neurotransmitter transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a neurotransmitter into, out of, within or between cells. Neurotransmitters are any chemical substance that is capable of transmitting (or inhibiting the transmission of) a nerve impulse from a neuron to another cell.

GOEntry.name: acetylcholine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of acetylcholine into, out of, within or between cells. Acetylcholine is an acetic acid ester of the organic base choline and functions as a neurotransmitter, released at the synapses of parasympathetic nerves and at neuromuscular junctions.

GOEntry.name: neurotransmitter:sodium symporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: neurotransmitter(out) + Na+(out) = neurotransmitter(in) + Na+(in).

GOEntry.name: norepinephrine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of norepinephrine into, out of, within or between cells. Norepinephrine (3,4-dihydroxyphenyl-2-aminoethanol) is a hormone secreted by the adrenal medulla and a neurotransmitter in the sympathetic peripheral nervous system and in some tracts of the CNS. It is also the biosynthetic precursor of epinephrine.

GOEntry.name: serotonin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of serotonin into, out of, within or between cells. Serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine) is a monoamine neurotransmitter occurring in the peripheral and central nervous systems.

GOEntry.name: organic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of organic acids, any acidic compound containing carbon in covalent linkage, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: organic acid:sodium symporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: organic acid(out) + Na+(out) = organic acid(in) + Na+(in).

GOEntry.name: phosphoglycerate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of phosphoglycerates into, out of, within or between cells. Phosphoglycerates are important intermediates in glycolysis and 3-phosphoglycerate is a precursor in serine biosynthesis.

GOEntry.name: urate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of urate into, out of, within or between cells. Urate is the anion of uric acid, 2,6,8-trioxypurine, the end product of purine metabolism in certain mammals and the main excretory product in uricotelic animals.

GOEntry.name: carboxylic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of carboxylic acids into, out of, within or between cells. Carboxylic acids are organic acids containing one or more carboxyl (COOH) groups or anions (COO-).

GOEntry.name: oxygen transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of oxygen into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: water transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of water (H2O) into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: carrier activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a specific substance or related group of substances from one side of the membrane to the other.

GOEntry.name: protein carrier activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of proteins from one side of the membrane to the other.

GOEntry.name: electron carrier activity
GOEntry.definition: Any molecular entity that serves as an electron acceptor and electron donor in an electron transport system.

GOEntry.name: electrochemical potential-driven transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the carrier-mediated transfer of one or more substances across a membrane. Transport occurs in three ways: uniport, a single species is transported by facilitated diffusion in a process not coupled to the utilization of a primary source of energy; antiport, two or more species are transported in opposite directions in a tightly coupled process not directly linked to a form of energy other than chemiosmotic energy; and symport, two or more species are transported together in the same direction in a tightly coupled process not directly linked to a form of energy other than chemiosmotic energy.

GOEntry.name: primary active transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of transport of a solute against a concentration gradient using a primary energy source. Primary energy sources known to be coupled to transport are chemical, electrical and solar sources.

GOEntry.name: intracellular transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of substances within a cell.

GOEntry.name: nucleocytoplasmic transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of substances between the nucleus and the cytoplasm of a cell.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: NADH dehydrogenase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: NADH + H+ + acceptor = NAD+ + reduced acceptor.

GOEntry.name: NADPH-hemoprotein reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + 2 ferricytochrome = NADP+ + 2 ferrocytochrome.

GOEntry.name: NADPH dehydrogenase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + acceptor = NADP+ + reduced acceptor.

GOEntry.name: cytochrome-b5 reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: NADH + H+ + 2 ferricytochrome b(5) = NAD+ + 2 ferrocytochrome b(5).

GOEntry.name: dihydrolipoyl dehydrogenase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: protein N6-(dihydrolipoyl)lysine + NAD+ = protein N6-(lipoyl)lysine + NADH + H+.

GOEntry.name: glutathione-disulfide reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 2 glutathione + NADP+ = glutathione disulfide + NADPH + H+.

GOEntry.name: sulfite reductase (NADPH) activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: H2S + 3 NADP+ + 3 H2O = SO3(2-) (sulfite) + 3 NADPH + 3 H+.

GOEntry.name: thioredoxin-disulfide reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + oxidized thioredoxin = NADP+ + reduced thioredoxin.

GOEntry.name: ferredoxin reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reactions: reduced ferredoxin + NAD+ = oxidized ferredoxin + NADH + H+ and reduced ferredoxin + NADP+ = oxidized ferredoxin + NADPH + H+.

GOEntry.name: electron donor activity
GOEntry.definition: Any substance that is able to transfer an electron to another chemical species.

GOEntry.name: electron acceptor activity
GOEntry.definition: Any substance to which an electron may be transferred.

GOEntry.name: electron carrier activity
GOEntry.definition: Any molecular entity that serves as an electron acceptor and electron donor in an electron transport system.

GOEntry.name: trypanothione-disulfide reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + trypanothione = NADP+ + reduced trypanothione.

GOEntry.name: leghemoglobin reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: NADPH + H+ + 2 ferrileghemoglobin = NADP+ + 2 ferroleghemoglobin.

GOEntry.name: rubredoxin reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reactions: reduced rubredoxin + NAD+ = oxidized rubredoxin + NADH + H+ and reduced rubredoxin + NADP+ = oxidized rubredoxin + NADPH + H+.

GOEntry.name: phthalate dioxygenase reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of electrons between pyridine nucleotides (obligatory two-electron carriers) and hemes or (2Fe-2S) centers (obligatory one-electron carriers) in respiration, photosynthesis, and many oxygenase systems.

GOEntry.name: methane monooxygenase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: methane + NADPH + O2 = methanol + NADP+ + H2O.

GOEntry.name: [methionine synthase] reductase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: (methionine synthase)-cob(II)alamin + NADPH + H+ + S-adenosyl methionine = (methionine synthase)-methylcob(I)alamin + S-adenosylhomocysteine + NADP+.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter, transferring electrons within CoQH2-cytochrome c reductase complex activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons within the CoQH2-cytochrome c reductase complex.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter, transferring electrons within cytochrome c oxidase complex activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons within the cytochrome c oxidase complex.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter, transferring electrons from CoQH2-cytochrome c reductase complex and cytochrome c oxidase complex activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons from the CoQH2-cytochrome c reductase complex and the cytochrome c oxidase complex.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter, transferring electrons within the cyclic electron transport pathway of photosynthesis activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons within the cyclic electron transport pathway of photosynthesis.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter, transferring electrons within the noncyclic electron transport pathway of photosynthesis activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons within the noncyclic electron transport pathway of photosynthesis.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter, transferring electrons within cytochrome b6/f complex of photosystem II activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons within the cytochrome b6/f complex of photosystem II.

GOEntry.name: electron transporter, transferring electrons from cytochrome b6/f complex of photosystem II activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of electrons from the cytochrome b6/f complex of photosystem II.

GOEntry.name: protein transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of proteins into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: protein carrier activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of proteins from one side of the membrane to the other.

GOEntry.name: delta-pH-dependent transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Transports proteins across membranes and transportation is dependent on pH gradient across the membranes.

GOEntry.name: protein-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + protein(out) = ADP + phosphate + protein(in).

GOEntry.name: colicin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a colicin into, out of, within or between cells. Colicins are a group of antibiotics produced by E. coli and related species that are encoded by a group of naturally occurring plasmids, e.g. Col E1.

GOEntry.name: lipoprotein transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of any conjugated, water-soluble protein in which the nonprotein moiety consists of a lipid or lipids, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: MAPK transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of MAP kinase into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: MAPK phosphatase transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of MAPK phosphatase into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: ion transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of charged atoms or small charged molecules into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: cation transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of atoms or small molecules with a positive charge into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: anion transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of atoms or small molecules with a negative charge into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: uptake permease activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the stereospecific transfer of a substrate across a biological membrane into a cell.

GOEntry.name: ATPase activity, coupled to transmembrane movement of ions
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate, to directly drive the transport of ions across a membrane.

GOEntry.name: metal ion transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of metal ions into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: carbohydrate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of carbohydrate into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: nucleotide-sugar transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of nucleotide-sugars into, out of, within or between cells. A nucleotide-sugars is any nucleotide in which the distal phosphoric residue of a nucleoside 5'-diphosphate is in glycosidic linkage with a monosaccharide or monosaccharide derivative.

GOEntry.name: protein-N(PI)-phosphohistidine-sugar phosphotransferase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: protein N-phosphohistidine + sugar(out) = protein histidine + sugar phosphate(in).

GOEntry.name: sialic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of sialic acid into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: oligosaccharide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of oligosaccharide into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: polysaccharide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of polysaccharides into, out of, within or between cells. A polysaccharide is a polymer of more than about 10 monosaccharide residues joined by glycosidic linkages.

GOEntry.name: hexuronide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of hexuronide into, out of, within or between cells. Hexuronides are any compound formed by combination of glycosidic linkage of a hydroxy compound (e.g. an alcohol or a saccharide) with the anomeric carbon atom of a hexuronate.

GOEntry.name: carbohydrate-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate to directly drive the transport of carbohydrates across a membrane.

GOEntry.name: sugar transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a sugar into, out of, within or between cells. A sugar is any member of a class of sweet, water-soluble, crystallizable carbohydrates, which are the monosaccharides and smaller oligosaccharides.

GOEntry.name: peptide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of peptides, compounds of two or more amino acids where the alpha carboxyl group of one is bound to the alpha amino group of another, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: oligopeptide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of oligopeptides into, out of, within or between cells. Oligopeptides are molecules that contain a small number (2 to 20) of amino-acid residues connected by peptide linkages.

GOEntry.name: peptide-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + peptide(in) = ADP + phosphate + peptide(out). Peptides exported include alpha-hemolysin, cyclolysin, colicin V and siderophores from Gram-negative bacteria, and bacteriocin, subtilin, competence factor and pediocin from Gram-positive bacteria.

GOEntry.name: peptidoglycan peptide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of peptidoglycan peptides into, out of, within or between cells. Peptidoglycan peptides are the oligopeptides found in peptidoglycan networks which cross-link the polysaccharide chains.

GOEntry.name: dipeptide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a dipeptide, a combination of two amino acids by means of a peptide (-CO-NH-) link, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: tripeptide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a tripeptide, a compound containing three amino acids linked together by peptide bonds, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: drug transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a drug into, out of, within or between cells. A drug is any naturally occurring or synthetic substance, other than a nutrient, that, when administered or applied to an organism, affects the structure or functioning of the organism; in particular, any such substance used in the diagnosis, prevention, or treatment of disease.

GOEntry.name: dopamine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of dopamine into, out of, within or between cells. Dopamine is a catecholamine neurotransmitter and a metabolic precursor of noradrenaline and adrenaline.

GOEntry.name: triose-phosphate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the exchange of an organic three carbon compound phosphate ester for inorganic phosphate.

GOEntry.name: multidrug transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of drugs into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: amiloride transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of amiloride of amiloride into, out of, within or between cells. Amiloride is a potent and specific inhibitor of sodium ion entry into cells. It is used as a potassium-sparing diuretic.

GOEntry.name: benomyl transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of benomyl into, out of, within or between cells. Benomyl, methyl 1-(butylcarbamoyl)-2-benzimidazolecarbamate, is a systemic agricultural fungicide used for control of certain fungal diseases of stone fruit.

GOEntry.name: drug:hydrogen antiporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: H+(out) + drug(in) = H+(in) + drug(out).

GOEntry.name: organomercurial transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of organomercurial compounds into, out of, within or between cells. Organomercurial substances are any organic compound containing a mercury atom.

GOEntry.name: carbonyl cyanide m-chlorophenylhydrazone transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of carbonyl cyanide m-chlorophenylhydrazone into, out of, within or between cells. Carbonyl cyanide m-chlorophenylhydrazone is a proton ionophore, commonly used as an uncoupling agent and inhibitor of photosynthesis because of its effects on mitochondrial and chloroplast membranes.

GOEntry.name: acriflavin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of acriflavin into, out of, within or between cells. Acriflavin is a fluorescent dye used as a local antiseptic and also as a biological stain. It intercalates into nucleic acids thereby inhibiting bacterial and viral replication.

GOEntry.name: alkane transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of alkanes into, out of, within or between cells. Alkanes are saturated aliphatic hydrocarbon compounds.

GOEntry.name: antibiotic transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: The directed movement of an antibiotic, a substance produced by or derived from certain fungi, bacteria, and other organisms, that can destroy or inhibit the growth of other microorganisms, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: daunorubicin-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + daunorubicin(in) = ADP + phosphate + daunorubicin(out).

GOEntry.name: azole transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of azoles, heterocyclic compound found in many biologically important substances, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: channel or pore class transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Allows facilitated diffusion (by an energy-independent process) by passage through a transmembrane aqueous pore or channel without a carrier-mediated mechanism. They do not exhibit stereospecificity but may be specific for a particular molecular species or class of molecules.

GOEntry.name: alpha-type channel activity
GOEntry.definition: Allows the movement of solutes by energy-independent process by passage through a transmembrane aqueous pore. Usually consist of alpha-helical membrane spanners, although beta-strands may be present and contribute to channel.

GOEntry.name: porin activity
GOEntry.definition: Allows the energy independent passage of small (less than 1000 Da) solutes across a membrane. The transmembrane portions of porins consist exclusively of beta-strands which form a beta-barrel. They are found in the outer membranes of Gram-negative bacteria, mitochondria, plastids and possibly acid-fast Gram-positive bacteria.

GOEntry.name: group translocator activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the PEP-dependent, phosphoryl transfer-driven transport of substances across a membrane.

GOEntry.name: protein-N(PI)-phosphohistidine-sugar phosphotransferase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: protein N-phosphohistidine + sugar(out) = protein histidine + sugar phosphate(in).

GOEntry.name: auxiliary transport protein activity
GOEntry.definition: Facilitates transport across one or more biological membranes but do not themselves participate directly in transport. These proteins always function in conjunction with one or more established transport systems. They may provide a function connected with energy coupling to transport, play a structural role in complex formation, serve a biogenic or stability function or function in regulation.

GOEntry.name: low voltage-gated potassium channel auxiliary protein activity
channel localizer activity
GOEntry.definition: Functions to locate the position of ion channels in the cell.

GOEntry.name: permease activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the stereospecific transfer of a substrate across a biological membrane.

GOEntry.name: efflux permease activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the stereospecific transfer of a substrate across a biological membrane out of a cell.

GOEntry.name: uptake permease activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the stereospecific transfer of a substrate across a biological membrane into a cell.

GOEntry.name: peptidoglycan transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of peptidoglycans, a class of glycoconjugates found in bacterial cell walls, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: peptidoglycan peptide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of peptidoglycan peptides into, out of, within or between cells. Peptidoglycan peptides are the oligopeptides found in peptidoglycan networks which cross-link the polysaccharide chains.

GOEntry.name: alcohol transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of an alcohol, any carbon-containing compound containing a hydroxyl group, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: sphingosine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of the amino alcohol sphingosine into, out of, within, or between cells.

GOEntry.name: polyol transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of polyols, polyhydric alcohols, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: nucleobase, nucleoside, nucleotide and nucleic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: nucleoside transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a nucleoside, a nucleobase linked to either beta-D-ribofuranose (ribonucleoside) or 2-deoxy-beta-D-ribofuranose, (a deoxyribonucleotide), into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: nucleobase transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a nucleobase, any nitrogenous base that is a constituent of a nucleoside, nucleotide, or nucleic acid, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: nucleotide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a nucleotide, any compound consisting of a nucleoside that is esterified with (ortho)phosphate, into, out of or within a cell.

GOEntry.name: DNA-protein complex transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of DNA-protein complexes into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: nucleic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of nucleic acids, single or double-stranded polynucleotides involved in the storage, transmission and transfer of genetic information, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: toxin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a toxin into, out of, within or between cells. A toxin is a poisonous compound (typically a protein) that is produced by cells or organisms and that can cause disease when introduced into the body or tissues of an organism.

GOEntry.name: nitric oxide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of nitric oxide, nitrogen monoxide, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: ATPase activity, coupled to transmembrane movement of substances
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate to directly drive the transport of a substance across a membrane.

GOEntry.name: channel-conductance-controlling ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate. An animal enzyme that is active in forming a chloride channel, the absence of which brings about cystic fibrosis. It is also involved in the functioning of other transmembrane channels.

GOEntry.name: eye pigment precursor transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + eye pigment precursor(in) = ADP + phosphate + eye pigment precursor(out).

GOEntry.name: guanine-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + guanine(out) = ADP + phosphate + guanine(in).

GOEntry.name: xenobiotic-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + xenobiotic(in) = ADP + phosphate + xenobiotic(out).

GOEntry.name: steroid-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + steroid(in) = ADP + phosphate + steroid(out).

GOEntry.name: polyamine-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + polyamine(out) = ADP + phosphate + polyamine(in).

GOEntry.name: quaternary-ammonium-compound-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + quaternary amine(out) = ADP + phosphate + quaternary amine(in).

GOEntry.name: cobalamin-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + cobalamin(out) = ADP + phosphate + cobalamin(in). Cobalamin = vitamin B12.

GOEntry.name: oligosaccharide-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + oligosaccharide(out) = ADP + phosphate + oligosaccharide(in).

GOEntry.name: amino acid-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + amino acid(out) = ADP + phosphate + amino acid(in).

GOEntry.name: glycerol-3-phosphate-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + glycerol-3-phosphate(out) = ADP + phosphate + glycerol-3-phosphate(in).

GOEntry.name: glutathione S-conjugate-exporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + glutathione S-conjugate(in) = ADP + phosphate + glutathione S-conjugate(out).

GOEntry.name: bile acid-exporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: bile acid(in) + ATP + H2O = bile acid(out) + ADP + phosphate.

GOEntry.name: capsular-polysaccharide-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + capsular polysaccharide(in) = ADP + phosphate + capsular polysaccharide(out).

GOEntry.name: lipopolysaccharide-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + lipopolysaccharide(in) = ADP + phosphate + lipopolysaccharide(out).

GOEntry.name: teichoic-acid-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + teichoic acid(in) = ADP + phosphate + teichoic acid(out).

GOEntry.name: heme-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + heme(in) = ADP + phosphate + heme(out).

GOEntry.name: peptide-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + peptide(in) = ADP + phosphate + peptide(out). Peptides exported include alpha-hemolysin, cyclolysin, colicin V and siderophores from Gram-negative bacteria, and bacteriocin, subtilin, competence factor and pediocin from Gram-positive bacteria.

GOEntry.name: beta-glucan-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + beta-glucan(in) = ADP + phosphate + beta-glucan(out).

GOEntry.name: protein-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + protein(out) = ADP + phosphate + protein(in).

GOEntry.name: thiamin pyrophosphate-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + thiamin pyrophosphate(out) = ADP + phosphate + thiamin pyrophosphate(in).

GOEntry.name: iron-chelate-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + iron chelate(out) = ADP + phosphate + iron chelate(in). Fe-enterobactin, Fe-dicitrate, Fe-hydroxamate and other siderophores are imported.

GOEntry.name: ATPase activity, coupled to transmembrane movement of ions
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate, to directly drive the transport of ions across a membrane.

GOEntry.name: antimonite-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + antimonite(in) = ADP + phosphate + antimonite(out).

GOEntry.name: carbohydrate-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate to directly drive the transport of carbohydrates across a membrane.

GOEntry.name: daunorubicin-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + daunorubicin(in) = ADP + phosphate + daunorubicin(out).

GOEntry.name: sphingolipid-translocating ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the movement of sphingolipids from one membrane face to the other ('flippase' activity), driven by the hydrolysis of ATP.

GOEntry.name: thiamin-transporting ATPase activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O + thiamin(out) = ADP + phosphate + thiamin(in).

GOEntry.name: amide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of an amide, any compound containing one, two, or three acyl groups attached to a nitrogen atom, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: xenobiotic transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a xenobiotic, a compound foreign to living organisms, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: benomyl transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of benomyl into, out of, within or between cells. Benomyl, methyl 1-(butylcarbamoyl)-2-benzimidazolecarbamate, is a systemic agricultural fungicide used for control of certain fungal diseases of stone fruit.

GOEntry.name: nalidixic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of nalidixic acid into, out of, within or between cells. Nalidixic acid is a synthetic antibiotic that interferes with DNA gyrase and inhibits prokaryotic replication.

GOEntry.name: acriflavin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of acriflavin into, out of, within or between cells. Acriflavin is a fluorescent dye used as a local antiseptic and also as a biological stain. It intercalates into nucleic acids thereby inhibiting bacterial and viral replication.

GOEntry.name: acridine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of acridine (10-azaanthracene), a heterocyclic ring compound found in crude coal-tar anthracene, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: benzoate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of benzoate, the anion of benzoic acid (benzenecarboxylic acid) into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: 3-hydroxyphenylpropionic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of 3-hydroxyphenylpropionic acid into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: alkanesulfonate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of alkanesulfonate into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: siderophore transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of siderophores, low molecular weight Fe(III)-chelating substances, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: siderophore-iron transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: siderophore-iron(out) + H+(out) = siderophore-iron(in) + H+(in).

GOEntry.name: ferrichrome transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a ferrichrome into, out of, within or between cells. Ferrichromes are any of a group of growth-promoting Fe(III) chelates formed by various genera of microfungi. They are homodetic cyclic hexapeptides made up of a tripeptide of glycine (or other small neutral amino acids) and a tripeptide of an N'acyl-N4-hydroxy-L-ornithine.

GOEntry.name: enterobactin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of the siderochrome enterochelin, a cyclic trimer of 2, 3 dihydroxybenzoylserine into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: chrysobactin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of the siderophore chrysobactin (alpha-N-(2,3-dihydroxybenzoyl)-D-lysyl-L-serine) into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: achromobactin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of achromobactin, a citrate siderophore, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: lactone transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of lactone, any of a series of organic compounds, regarded as anhydrides of certain hydroxy acids, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: boron transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Catalysis of the transport of boron across a membrane against the concentration gradient.

GOEntry.name: vitamin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of vitamins into, out of, within or between cells. A vitamin is one of a number of unrelated organic substances that occur in many foods in small amounts and that are necessary in trace amounts for the normal metabolic functioning of the body.

GOEntry.name: folic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of folic acid (pteroylglutamic acid) into, out of, within or between cells. Folic acid is widely distributed as a member of the vitamin B complex and is essential for the synthesis of purine and pyrimidines.

GOEntry.name: biotin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of biotin into, out of, within or between cells. Biotin is cis-tetrahydro-2-oxothieno(3,4-d)imidazoline-4-valeric acid; the (+) enantiomer is very widely distributed in cells and serves as a carrier in a number of enzymatic beta-carboxylation reactions.

GOEntry.name: carnitine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of carnitine into, out of, within or between cells. Carnitine is a compound that participates in the transfer of acyl groups across the inner mitochondrial membrane.

GOEntry.name: L-ascorbic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of L-ascorbate into, out of, within or between cells. L-ascorbate is a six-carbon carbohydrate-like compound found in fruit and vegetables. It has vitamin C activity in humans and guinea pigs.

GOEntry.name: pantothenate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of pantothenate into, out of, within or between cells. Pantothenate is the anion of pantothenic acid, the amide of beta-alanine and pantoic acid; it is a B complex vitamin that is a constituent of coenzyme A and is distributed ubiquitously in foods.

GOEntry.name: thiamin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of thiamin into, out of, within or between cells. Thiamin is vitamin B1, a water soluble vitamin present in fresh vegetables and meats, especially liver.

GOEntry.name: cobalamin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of cobalamin (vitamin B12), a water-soluble vitamin characterized by possession of a corrin nucleus containing a cobalt atom, into, out of or within a cell.

GOEntry.name: cofactor transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a cofactor into, out of, within or between cells. A cofactor is a substance that is required for the activity of an enzyme or other protein.

GOEntry.name: S-adenosylmethionine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of S-adenosylmethionine, S-(5'-adenosyl)-L-methionine, an important intermediate in one-carbon metabolism, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: creatine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of creatine into, out of, within or between cells. Creatine is a compound synthesized from the amino acids arginine, glycine, and methionine that occurs in muscle.

GOEntry.name: folic acid transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of folic acid (pteroylglutamic acid) into, out of, within or between cells. Folic acid is widely distributed as a member of the vitamin B complex and is essential for the synthesis of purine and pyrimidines.

GOEntry.name: biopterin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of biopterin into, out of, within or between cells. Biopterin is a growth factor for certain protozoans and some insects; it is widely distributed in tissues and functions in a reduced form, tetrahydrobiopterin, as a hydroxylation coenzyme.

GOEntry.name: biotin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of biotin into, out of, within or between cells. Biotin is cis-tetrahydro-2-oxothieno(3,4-d)imidazoline-4-valeric acid; the (+) enantiomer is very widely distributed in cells and serves as a carrier in a number of enzymatic beta-carboxylation reactions.

GOEntry.name: carnitine transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of carnitine into, out of, within or between cells. Carnitine is a compound that participates in the transfer of acyl groups across the inner mitochondrial membrane.

GOEntry.name: FAD transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of flavin-adenine dinucleotide (FAD) into, out of, within or between cells. FAD forms the coenzyme of the prosthetic group of various flavoprotein oxidoreductase enzymes, in which it functions as an electron acceptor by being reversibly converted to its reduced form.

GOEntry.name: heme transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of heme, any compound of iron complexed in a porphyrin (tetrapyrrole) ring, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: pantothenate transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of pantothenate into, out of, within or between cells. Pantothenate is the anion of pantothenic acid, the amide of beta-alanine and pantoic acid; it is a B complex vitamin that is a constituent of coenzyme A and is distributed ubiquitously in foods.

GOEntry.name: nicotinamide mononucleotide transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of nicotinamide mononucleotide into, out of, within or between cells. Nicotinamide mononucleotide is a ribonucleotide in which the nitrogenous base, nicotinamide, is in beta-n-glycosidic linkage with the c-1 position of d-ribose. It is a constituent of NAD and NADP.

GOEntry.name: achromobactin transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of achromobactin, a citrate siderophore, into, out of, within or between cells.

GOEntry.name: coenzyme transporter activity
GOEntry.definition: Enables the directed movement of a coenzyme into, out of, within or between cells. A coenzyme is any of various nonprotein organic cofactors that are required, in addition to an enzyme and a substrate, for an enzymatic reaction to proceed.

GOEntry.name: binding
GOEntry.definition: The selective and stoichiometric interaction of a molecule with one or more specific sites on another molecule.

GOEntry.name: acyl binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with an acyl group, any group formally derived by removal of the hydroxyl group from the acid function of a carboxylic acid.

GOEntry.name: nucleotide binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a nucleotide, any compound consisting of a nucleoside that is esterified with (ortho)phosphate or an oligophosphate at any hydroxyl group on the glycose moiety.

GOEntry.name: methyl-CpG binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a methylated cystine/guanine dinucleotide.

GOEntry.name: FMN binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with FMN, flavin mononucleotide, the coenzyme or the prosthetic group of various flavoprotein oxidoreductase enzymes.

GOEntry.name: purine nucleotide binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with purine nucleotides, any compound consisting of a purine nucleoside esterified with (ortho)phosphate.

GOEntry.name: pyrimidine nucleotide binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with pyrimidine nucleotide, any compound consisting of a pyrimidine nucleoside esterified with (ortho)phosphate.

GOEntry.name: cyclic nucleotide binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a cyclic nucleotide, a nucleotide in which the phosphate group is in diester linkage to two positions on the sugar residue.

GOEntry.name: pattern binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a repeating or polymeric structure, such as a polysaccharide or peptidoglycan.

GOEntry.name: lipopolysaccharide binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with lipopolysaccharide.

GOEntry.name: lipoarabinomannan binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with lipoarabinomannan.

GOEntry.name: polysaccharide binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with any polysaccharide.

GOEntry.name: peptidoglycan binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively, in a non-covalent manner with peptidoglycan, any of a class of glycoconjugates found in bacterial cell walls.

GOEntry.name: nucleoside binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a nucleoside, a compound consisting of a purine or pyrimidine nitrogenous base linked either to ribose or deoxyribose.

GOEntry.name: purine nucleoside binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a purine nucleoside.

GOEntry.name: pyrimidine nucleoside binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with pyrimidine nucleoside.

GOEntry.name: nucleic acid binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with any nucleic acid.

GOEntry.name: DNA binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid).

GOEntry.name: RNA binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with an RNA molecule or a portion thereof.

GOEntry.name: translation factor activity, nucleic acid binding
GOEntry.definition: Functions during translation by binding nucleic acids during polypeptide synthesis at the ribosome.

GOEntry.name: translation repressor activity, nucleic acid binding
GOEntry.definition: Antagonizes the ribosome-mediated translation of mRNA into a polypeptide via direct binding to nucleic acid.

GOEntry.name: translation initiation factor activity
GOEntry.definition: Functions in the initiation of ribosome-mediated translation of mRNA into a polypeptide.

GOEntry.name: translation elongation factor activity
GOEntry.definition: Functions in chain elongation during polypeptide synthesis at the ribosome.

GOEntry.name: translation termination factor activity
GOEntry.definition: Functions in the termination of translation.

GOEntry.name: translation activator activity
GOEntry.definition: Any of a group of soluble proteins functioning in the activation of ribosome-mediated translation of mRNA into a polypeptide.

GOEntry.name: antigen binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with an antigen, any substance which is capable of inducing a specific immune response and of reacting with the products of that response, the specific antibody or specifically sensitized T-lymphocytes, or both. Binding may counteract the biological activity of the antigen.

GOEntry.name: toxin binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a toxin, a poisonous substance that causes damage to biological systems. Toxins are differentiated from simple chemical poisons and vegetable alkaloids by their high molecular weight and antigenicity (they elicit an antibody response).

GOEntry.name: lipid antigen binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a lipid antigen.

GOEntry.name: peptide antigen binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with an antigen peptide, a fragment of a foreign protein derived by proteolysis within the cell.

GOEntry.name: receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with one or more specific sites on a receptor molecule, a macromolecule that undergoes combination with a hormone, neurotransmitter, drug or intracellular messenger to initiate a change in cell function.

GOEntry.name: opioid peptide activity
GOEntry.definition: Naturally occurring peptide that is an opioid (any non-alkaloid having an opiate-like effect that can be reversed by naloxone or other recognized morphine antagonist). These include Leu- and Met-enkephalin, dynorphin and neoendorphin, alpha, beta, gamma and delta endorphins formed from beta-lipotropin, various pronase-resistant peptides such as beta casamorphin, and other peptides whose opiate-like action seems to be indirect.

GOEntry.name: G-protein-coupled receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a G-protein-coupled receptor.

GOEntry.name: Notch binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the Notch (N) protein, a surface receptor.

GOEntry.name: patched binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the patched (ptc) protein, a receptor for hedgehog proteins.

GOEntry.name: receptor tyrosine kinase-like orphan receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interaction with the receptor tyrosine kinase-like orphan receptor (Ror).

GOEntry.name: wishful thinking binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with wishful thinking (Wit), a type II bone morphogenic protein receptor.

GOEntry.name: sevenless binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the sevenless (sev) protein, a receptor tyrosine kinase.

GOEntry.name: smoothened binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the smoothened (smo) protein, which interacts with patched to transmit hedgehog signals.

GOEntry.name: Toll binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the Toll protein, a transmembrane receptor.

GOEntry.name: torso binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the torso (tor) protein, a receptor tyrosine kinase.

GOEntry.name: death receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a death receptor.

GOEntry.name: scavenger receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with scavenger receptors, a family of proteins that are expressed on myeloid cells and are involved in the uptake of effete cellular components and foreign particles.

GOEntry.name: cytokine activity
GOEntry.definition: Functions to control the survival, growth, differentiation and effector function of tissues and cells.

GOEntry.name: epidermal growth factor receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the epidermal growth factor receptor.

GOEntry.name: insulin receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the insulin receptor.

GOEntry.name: insulin-like growth factor receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the insulin-like growth factor receptor.

GOEntry.name: transforming growth factor beta receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the transforming growth factor beta receptor.

GOEntry.name: integrin binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with an integrin.

GOEntry.name: hormone activity
GOEntry.definition: Any substance formed in very small amounts in one specialized organ or group of cells and carried (sometimes in the bloodstream) to another organ or group of cells, in the same organism, upon which it has a specific regulatory action. The term was originally applied to agents with a stimulatory physiological action in vertebrate animals (as opposed to a chalone, which has a depressant action). Usage is now extended to regulatory compounds in lower animals and plants, and to synthetic substances having comparable effects.

GOEntry.name: pheromone activity
GOEntry.definition: The activity of binding to and activating specific cell surface receptors, thereby inducing behavioral, developmental, or physiological response(s) from a responding organism or cell. The substance may be released or retained on the cell surface. Pheromones may serve as a specific attractant, social communicator, or sexual stimulant.

GOEntry.name: growth factor activity
GOEntry.definition: The function that stimulates a cell to grow or proliferate. Most growth factors have other actions besides the induction of cell growth or proliferation.

GOEntry.name: sulfonylurea receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the sulfonylurea receptor, a regulatory subunit of the ATP-sensitive potassium ion channel.

GOEntry.name: aryl hydrocarbon receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with an aryl hydrocarbon receptor.

GOEntry.name: benzodiazepine receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with the peripheral benzodiazepine receptor (PBR).

GOEntry.name: semaphorin receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with semaphorin receptors.

GOEntry.name: intercellular adhesion molecule-3 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with receptors for intercellular adhesion molecule-3 (ICAM-3), such as DC-SIGN and LFA-1.

GOEntry.name: receptor tyrosine kinase binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a receptor that possesses protein tyrosine kinase activity.

GOEntry.name: high molecular weight kininogen receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a high molecular weight kininogen receptor.

GOEntry.name: glutamate receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a glutamate receptor.

GOEntry.name: nuclear hormone receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a nuclear hormone receptor, a ligand-dependent receptor found in the nucleus of the cell.

GOEntry.name: MHC protein binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with major histocompatibility complex molecules; a set of molecules displayed on cell surfaces that are responsible for lymphocyte recognition and antigen presentation.

GOEntry.name: T-cell receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a T-cell receptor, the antigen-recognizing receptor on the surface of T-cells.

GOEntry.name: CD4 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a CD4, a receptor found on the surface of T-cells, monocytes and macrophages.

GOEntry.name: CD8 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a CD8, a receptor found on the surface of thymocytes and cytotoxic and suppressor T-lymphocytes.

GOEntry.name: CD70 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a CD70, a receptor found on the surface of most activated B-cells and some activated T-cells.

GOEntry.name: CD154 receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with CD154, a receptor found on the surface of some activated lymphocytes.

GOEntry.name: neuromedin U receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with one or more specific sites on a neuromedin U receptor.

GOEntry.name: peroxisome proliferator activated receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with any of the peroxisome proliferator activated receptors, alpha, beta or gamma.

GOEntry.name: natural killer cell lectin-like receptor binding
GOEntry.definition: Interacting selectively with a lectin-like natural killer cell receptor.

GOEntry.name: host cell surface receptor binding
